<p><strong>Long-tailed Weasel (<em>Mustela frenata</em>)</strong></p>
<p><strong>Family: </strong>Mustelidae<br />
<strong>Genus Species: </strong><em>Mustela frenata</em><br />
<strong>Common Name: </strong>Long-tailed Weasel<br /><p>
<p><strong>Identification</strong></p>
<p>The Long-tailed Weasel has a body length of 9-10½ inches for males and 8-9 inches for females, a tail length of 4-6 inches (males) and 3-5 inches (female), and a weight of 198-340 grams (males) and 85-198 grams (females). It has a long slender body, long neck, yellowish- white underparts, and a black tip on the tail. It is the most widely distributed weasel, being found almost anywhere in the continental U.S. For a more detailed overview of this species see 〔<a href="http://www.enature.com/fieldguides/detail.asp?allSpecies=y&#038;searchText=long-tailed%20weasel&#038;curGroupID=5&#038;lgfromWhere=&#038;curPageNum=1">eNature</a>〕.</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p><strong>Habitat Associations and Natural History</strong></p>
<p>This weasel has no specific habitat, it is found in all land habitats near water. It is mainly nocturnal, but also active during the day. It climbs trees, but spends most of its time on ground. It feeds mostly on small mammals up to a rabbit’s size, as well as on birds and other animals. It kills by piercing the skull with canines. It usually nests in burrows of other animals, sometimes under wood or rock piles. It bears 4-8 young in late April or early May with a gestation period of 205-337 days.</p>
